e to become a lawyer, a Confederate officer in the Civil War, and mayor of San Antonio. His remarkable name came from a Russian prince admired by the mission family."},{"number":2,"category":"legacy","header":"His lost house surfaced in a school dig","body":"In 2025, archaeology during construction at San Antonio’s Fox Tech High School campus uncovered the remnants of the Newton House, his former home, in the south parking lot. The dig also exposed the 1700s San Pedro Acequia irrigation system nearby."}],"videos":[{"video_id":"VID002"}],"slug":"samuel-galitzin-newton-1823"},"I01798":{"id":"I01798","classification":{"is_thomas_descendant":false,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_easter_egg":false,"generation_from_thomas":null},"bio":{"display_name":"Mary Elizabeth Tompkins Newton","first_name":"Mary Elizabeth","last_name":"Newton","married_names":[],"maiden_name":"Tompkins"},"birth":{"year":1830,"date_precision":"exact","month":12,"day":12},"death":{"year":1878,"date_precision":"exact","month":1,"day":8,"city":"San Antonio","state":"Texas","country":"United States"},"parents":{"father_id":null,"mother_id":null},"marriages":[{"spouse_id":"HD6474","marriage_number":1,"date_year":1854,"children_ids":["HD6483","HD6484","HD6485","HD6486","HD6487","HD6488","HD6489"]}],"tags":[],"burial":{"cemetery_id":"CEM892"},"slug":"mary-elizabeth-tompkins-1830"},"HD6470":{"id":"HD6470","classification":{"is_thomas_descendant":true,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_easter_egg":false,"generation_from_thomas":8},"bio":{"display_name":"Rev. Samuel Newton","first_name":"Samuel","last_name":"Newton","married_names":[],"title":"Rev.","photo_url":"https://res.cloudinary.com/dc5clrqtw/image/upload/v1781541724/samnewton_zhjlhs.png","bio_blurb":"Osage and Cherokee missionary; San Antonio pioneer"},"birth":{"year":1792,"date_precision":"exact","month":1,"day":1,"city":"Woodbridge","state":"Connecticut","country":"United States"},"death":{"year":1865,"date_precision":"exact","month":5,"day":23,"city":"San Antonio","state":"Texas","country":"United States"},"parents":{"father_id":"HD0082","mother_id":null},"marriages":[{"spouse_id":"I01795","marriage_number":1,"date_year":1813,"date_month":1,"date_day":4,"children_ids":["HD6471","HD6472","HD6473"]},{"spouse_id":"I01796","marriage_number":2,"date_year":1822,"date_month":6,"date_day":3,"children_ids":["HD6474","HD6475","HD6476","HD6477","HD6478","HD6479","HD6480"]},{"spouse_id":"I01797","marriage_number":3,"date_year":1835,"date_month":7,"date_day":27,"children_ids":["HD6481","HD6482"]}],"tags":["minister","missionary","cherokee_mission","westward_migration"],"burial":{"cemetery_id":"CEM891"},"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"religion","header":"He buried a wife and child mid-journey","body":"In 1821 Samuel Newton, his wife Betsey, and their children set out from New York with the United Foreign Missionary Society to establish Harmony Mission among the Osage. On the journey Betsey died near Shawneetown, Illinois, days after their newborn died near Louisville — a double loss before the mission was even reached."},{"number":2,"category":"religion","header":"He married two missionary widows in turn","body":"Widowed on the trail, Samuel married Mary Hunt McCarty at Harmony Mission in 1822, the widow of fellow missionary John Seeley. After Mary died in 1835 he married a third missionary widow, Sophia Palmer Joslyn, whose first husband had also died in the field."},{"number":3,"category":"migration","header":"The first Protestant to settle San Antonio","body":"After missions to the Osage and Cherokee, Samuel brought his family to San Antonio in 1848, when the town had scarcely a shingled roof among its adobe houses. Family record holds he was the first Protestant to settle there permanently; he opened a private school and helped found the city’s First Presbyterian Church."},{"number":4,"category":"character","header":"Six generations of Samuels before him","body":"Rev. Samuel Newton was the sixth Samuel Newton in unbroken succession — Samuel son of Samuel son of Samuel, back six generations to the immigrant minister Roger Newton. He carried that Connecticut lineage from a Woodbridge parsonage to the Texas frontier."}],"cross_connections":[{"type":"civic_connection","related_id":"X02122","link_text":"Ainsworth Blunt","display_label":"served the same Cherokee mission field in Indian Territory"}],"slug":"samuel-newton-1792"},"I01796":{"id":"I01796","classification":{"is_thomas_descendant":false,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_easter_egg":false,"generation_from_thomas":null},"bio":{"display_name":"Mary Hunt McCarty Newton","first_name":"Mary Hunt","last_name":"Newton","married_names":[],"maiden_name":"McCarty"},"birth":{"year":1802,"date_precision":"exact","month":7,"day":19,"city":"Pompton","state":"New Jersey","country":"United States"},"death":{"year":1835,"date_precision":"exact","month":11,"day":21,"city":"Park Hill","state":"Oklahoma","country":"United States"},"parents":{"father_id":null,"mother_id":null},"marriages":[{"spouse_id":"HD6470","marriage_number":2,"date_year":1822,"children_ids":["HD6474","HD6475","HD6476","HD6477","HD6478","HD6479","HD6480"]}],"tags":[],"slug":"mary-hunt-mccarty-1802"}},"burialCemetery":{"id":"CEM893","name":"Marfa Cemetery","city":"Marfa","state":"Texas","country":"United States","gps":{"lat":30.30825,"lng":-104.03899}},"institutionsById":{},"crossConnections":[]}